In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April 6-12, 2015, as National Public Health Week. He acknowledges the efforts of public health professionals in combating the Ebola outbreak in West Africa and emphasizes the importance of supporting public health with determination and purpose. The article also highlights the connection between public health and the environment, with climate change posing new threats to the well-being of individuals, particularly those with asthma. The Obama Administration is committed to combating the health impacts of climate change and has proposed carbon pollution limits for power plants. The article also mentions the achievements of the Affordable Care Act, the Let's Move! initiative, and the Global Health Security Agenda in promoting wellness and prevention. Obama calls on citizens, government agencies, businesses, and organizations to take action to improve the health of the nation.